"Abstract Advances in digital technology have provided rights holders with the opportunity to develop new ways of formatting and distributing works but also allow unauthorized reproduction on an unprecedented scale. The digital age has made copying by private individuals easier, posing an increasing threat to the interests of rights holders. Whilst the law has developed to counter unlawful copying one suggestion is that technology itself can provide the solution: the often quoted phrase “the answer to the machine is in the machine”. There is no doubt that there has been a proliferation of copy protection devices and measures. Recent cases demonstrate that an effective legal framework is required to complement copy protection measures and stem the growth of unauthorized copying."
